This paper deals with mechanism design and auctions, which are typically studied in the subfield of computer science known as game theory (cs.GT). The paper also involves analyzing the performance of randomized mechanisms, which can be viewed as algorithms for making decisions under uncertainty, and thus could be categorized under computer science subfields such as data structures (cs.DS) or artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of reserve prices and the impact of unknown distributions on auction design, which are topics that fall under the subfields of economics and information theory, respectively (cs.EC, cs.IT).
